<section id="cam-quad-general">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-12">
                <h1 class="display-3 section-heading">Camera quad</h1>
                <p>
                    In 2013 I stated the making of a 500mm, foldable areal camera-platform. My challenge to myself was to manufacture the frame exclusively by the use of the 3D-printer so that the system would have to be modelled digitally.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The cam-quad has in the years since gone through multiple design iterations, evolving as I increased my knowledge of CAD-design, statics, 3D-printing and design principles.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<section id="cam-quad-development" class="feature-light">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row">
            <div class="float-lg">
                <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-5 feature-caption">
                    <h6>First prototype</h6>
                    <p>
                        The first prototype frame was made exclusively from <a target="_blank" href="http://taulman3d.com/bridge-nylon.html">Tulman Bridge</a> nylon filament. This material is very strong, but is more flexible than PLA/ABS. Each arm was printed separately with a compressive, horizontal member on top and a circular tensile member diagonally attached to the base of the main frame. The nylon was a temperamental material to print such large pieces with.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-7 text-sm-center">
